{"parse":{"title":"Burning of the Clavie","pageid":3026981,"revid":843556375,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Burning the clavie</b> is an ancient <a href=\"/wiki/Scotland\" title=\"Scotland\">Scottish</a> custom still observed at <a href=\"/wiki/Burghead\" title=\"Burghead\">Burghead</a>, a fishing village on the <a href=\"/wiki/Moray_Firth\" title=\"Moray Firth\">Moray Firth</a>. The <i>clavie</i> is a collection of <a href=\"/wiki/Cask\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Cask\">casks</a> split in two, lit as a <a href=\"/wiki/Bonfire\" title=\"Bonfire\">bonfire</a> in the evening of 11 January, i.e. New Year's Eve (in  Scotland, Hogmanay) by the <a href=\"/wiki/Julian_Calendar\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Julian Calendar\">Julian Calendar</a>. One of these casks is joined together again by a huge nail (Latin <i>clavis</i>; hence the term, it may also be from <a href=\"/wiki/Scottish_Gaelic_language\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Scottish Gaelic language\">Scottish Gaelic</a> <i>cliabh</i>, a basket used for holding combustibles). It is then filled with <a href=\"/wiki/Tar\" title=\"Tar\">tar</a>, lighted and carried flaming round the village and finally up to a headland upon which stands the ruins of an <a href=\"/wiki/Altar\" title=\"Altar\">altar</a>, locally called the <i>Doorie</i>. It here forms the nucleus of the bonfire, which is built up of split casks. When the burning tar-barrel falls in pieces, the people scramble to get a lighted piece with which to kindle the New Year's fire on their cottage hearth. The <a href=\"/wiki/Charcoal\" title=\"Charcoal\">charcoal</a> of the <i>clavie</i> is collected and put in pieces up the cottage chimneys, to keep spirits and witches from coming down.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<ul class=\"gallery mw-gallery-traditional\">\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:BurningOfTheClavie1(AnneBurgess)Jan1984.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/BurningOfTheClavie1%28AnneBurgess%29Jan1984.jpg/68px-BurningOfTheClavie1%28AnneBurgess%29Jan1984.jpg\" width=\"68\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/BurningOfTheClavie1%28AnneBurgess%29Jan1984.jpg/103px-BurningOfTheClavie1%28AnneBurgess%29Jan1984.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/BurningOfTheClavie1%28AnneBurgess%29Jan1984.jpg/137px-BurningOfTheClavie1%28AnneBurgess%29Jan1984.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"366\" data-file-height=\"640\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>The Burning of the Clavie celebrates New Year's Eve, old style, which falls on 11 January (unless 11 January is a Sunday, in which case the celebration is held on 10 January). The Clavie is a half-cask, mounted securely on a pole, and filled with staves of wood and inflammable liquid.\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:BurningOfTheClavie2(AnneBurgess)Jan1984.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f5/BurningOfTheClavie2%28AnneBurgess%29Jan1984.jpg/83px-BurningOfTheClavie2%28AnneBurgess%29Jan1984.jpg\" width=\"83\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f5/BurningOfTheClavie2%28AnneBurgess%29Jan1984.jpg/124px-BurningOfTheClavie2%28AnneBurgess%29Jan1984.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f5/BurningOfTheClavie2%28AnneBurgess%29Jan1984.jpg/165px-BurningOfTheClavie2%28AnneBurgess%29Jan1984.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"441\" data-file-height=\"640\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>The burning Clavie is carried through the streets of the town by the members of the Clavie Crew, who must be natives of the town to qualify. It is followed by a procession of hundreds of onlookers. On the route through the town, the Clavie Crew hands pieces of the Clavie - smouldering pieces of wood - to householders to ensure good luck for the ensuing year.\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:33.5px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:BurningOfTheClavie3(AnneBurgess)Jan1984.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/BurningOfTheClavie3%28AnneBurgess%29Jan1984.jpg/120px-BurningOfTheClavie3%28AnneBurgess%29Jan1984.jpg\" width=\"120\" height=\"83\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/BurningOfTheClavie3%28AnneBurgess%29Jan1984.jpg/180px-BurningOfTheClavie3%28AnneBurgess%29Jan1984.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/BurningOfTheClavie3%28AnneBurgess%29Jan1984.jpg/240px-BurningOfTheClavie3%28AnneBurgess%29Jan1984.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"640\" data-file-height=\"441\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>Finally the Clavie is carried to the top of the Doorie Hill and the pole is placed in a socket on top of the hill.\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n</ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Burning_of_the_Clavie&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-te